2025-03-16 15:39:03,730 - DEBUG - Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'files': None, 'json_data': {'messages': [{'role': 'user', 'content': "你是一位总结专家。你的任务是撰写总结。\n    以下是原始文档文本：\n    \n    TITLE:Equilibrium Data Mining and Data Abundance\nAbstract:We study theoretically how the proliferation of new data (“data abundance”) affects the allocation of capital between quantitative and nonquantitative asset managers (“data miners” and “experts”), their performance, and price informativeness. Data miners search for predictors of asset payoffs and select those with a sufficiently high precision. Data abundance raises the precision of the best predictors, but it can induce data miners to search less intensively for high-precision signals. In this case, their performance becomes more dispersed and they receive less capital. Nevertheless, data abundance always raises price informativeness and can therefore reduce asset managers' average\xa0performance.\nintroduction: “Quants have been helped by two transformative forces. Regulatory scrutiny has made it hard to obtain an edge through methods such as prodding company executives for information […] Even more importantly, investors have now at their fingertips an expanding ocean of data.”(“The quants run Wall Street now,”Wall Street Journal2017) An important role of activeasset managers is to produce information about asset fundamentals. By trading on this information, they make asset prices more informative. The way asset managers generate trading signals is changing, however. An increasing number of funds (“quants”) rely on quantitative techniques (statistical and computerized analysis of vast amount of data) rather than human judgment. For instance, Abis (2022) finds that quant funds account for18.6%$18.6\\%$of all U.S. active equity funds in 2017 versus6.10%$6.10\\%$in 2000.1Many industry commentators relate this trend to the big data revolution.2Yet, to our knowledge, the economic mechanism driving this relationship has not been formalized, leaving many questions unanswered. For instance, is the rise of quant funds inevitable? How does it affect the performance of active asset managers? And does it increase price efficiency? Our paper provides a benchmark rational expectations model to study this mechanism and address these questions. The model is unique in its ability to separate the effects of two facets of the big data revolution: (i) the proliferation of new data sets, “data abundance,” and (ii) lower data processing costs due to improvements in computing power. These are often comingled, as if both contribute to the reduction in the cost of information production. Yet, they are conceptually distinct. Alternative data such as sensors data or social media data are useful to predict future cash flows or returns and can improve the precision of signals that quant funds discover.3However, the emergence of new data does not in and of itself reduce data processing costs. Our central finding is that the effects of data abundance and those of lower data processing costs are not necessarily the same. In particular, as we explain below, these two dimensions of the big data revolution have different implications for the dynamics of the allocation of capital to quants and discretionary funds. Our model features risk-averse investors who allocate their capital to two types of asset managers: (i) experts and (ii) data miners. These two types of asset managers produce information about a risky asset using different technologies. Each expert has a predetermined ability (skill) to obtain a signal of a given precision. In contrast, data miners discover trading signals through a search process that comprises several rounds of exploration. In each round, each data miner can combine variables from different data sets (e.g., accounting data and social media data) to build a predictor of the asset payoff. The quality of this predictor,τ$\\tau$, is drawn from a distribution whose support ranges from zero (noise) toτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$(the data frontier). After each round, each data miner can decide to either launch a new round of exploration at costc$c$(the search cost) or stop searching. This process is repeated until each data miner finds a satisficing predictor. The market for the risky asset then opens and trading takes place between asset managers, dealers, and noise traders. We interpret experts as discretionary funds and data miners as quant funds. The former rely on expertise (e.g., industry knowledge) and judgmental analysis to generate investment ideas, while the latter systematically explores various data sets to discover new predictors (see Harvey et al. (2017) and Abis (2022)). Quants' search process requires (i) obtaining, cleaning and preparing new data for analysis, (ii) using statistical techniques to obtain a predictor based on these data, and (iii) deciding, via backtesting, whether a predictor is good enough for live trading (see Narang (2013)). One round of exploration comprises all of these steps and the exploration cost for the round is the total cost of executing each of these steps. We characterize the equilibrium of the model, that is, (i) the allocation of capital to data miners and experts, (ii) data miners' optimal search strategy, (iii) asset managers' optimal holdings, and (iv) the risky asset price such that asset managers and investors make optimal decisions and the asset market clears. In equilibrium, each data miner optimally stops searching once she finds a predictor whose quality exceeds an endogenous threshold,τ∗$\\tau ^*$. Thus, in equilibrium, the quality of data miners' predictors ranges fromτ∗$\\tau ^*$(least informative) toτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$(most informative). As a result, even though data miners are ex-ante homogeneous (same preferences and exploration costs), they are ex-post heterogeneous in the quality of their predictors and performance. When investors allocate capital to asset managers, they observe experts' skill level (signal precision) and correctly anticipate data miners' search strategy (τ∗$\\tau ^*$). Investors prefer to allocate capital to experts with skill aboveτ∗$\\tau ^*$than to data miners because their expected utility increases with asset managers' skill. However, each expert's capacity to serve investors is limited. Investors therefore optimally allocate capital to experts up to the point at which the marginal expert has a signal quality just equal toτ∗$\\tau ^*$and each expert operates at full capacity. The rest of investor capital is optimally allocated to data miners. This process determines the fraction of investor capital, denoted asμ∗$\\mu ^*$, allocated to data miners. Our novel implications derive from the effect of increasing the data frontierτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$(e.g., due to the availability of new data sets) or reducing data miners' search costsc$c$(e.g., due to greater computing power) on their search strategy (τ∗$\\tau ^*$) and the allocation of capital between data miners and experts (μ∗$\\mu ^*$).4 Consider a push back of the data frontier (i.e., an increase inτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$). This shock increases the expected trading profit of data miners who find the best predictor (the hidden gold nugget effect) since its quality becomes even larger. However, these data miners trade more aggressively on their signal (i.e., they make larger bets for a given deviation between the asset price and their forecast of its payoff) because they face less risk. As a result, the asset price is more informative (closer to the asset payoff), which reduces the expected profit of all data miners (the price informativeness effect). The first effect raises the value of searching for a better predictor after finding one while the second reduces it. Whenτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$is small, the hidden gold nugget effect dominates. Thus, a push back of the data frontier induces data miners to demand higher quality predictors (τ∗$\\tau ^*$increases in equilibrium) and investors shift capital from experts to data miners. However, whenτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$becomes large enough, a push back of the data frontier induces data miners to search less intensively (τ∗$\\tau ^*$decreases) and capital flows back to experts because the price informativeness effect dominates. In contrast, a decrease in data miners' search cost unambiguously raises the value of searching for another predictor after finding one because it reduces the total expected cost of search without directly affecting data miners' average trading aggressiveness. Thus, a reduction in data miners' search costs always leads them to be more demanding with respect to the quality of their predictors and induces investors to allocate relatively more capital to these funds. In sum, the model explains the growth in the relative size of quant funds by both a decrease in search costs (due, e.g., to improvements in computing power) and data abundance. However, it predicts that as the amount of data continues to grow, this trend should reverse itself. Thus, data abundance is both a catalyst for and a limit on the rise of quant funds. In equilibrium, a push back of the data frontier always triggers an improvement in the average quality of the signals used by all asset managers (even though it can reduce data miners' search intensity), as does a reduction in data miners' search costs. Thus, a push back of the data frontier or a decrease in data miners' search costs increases the informativeness of the risky asset price. For these reasons, asset managers' (cross-sectional) average performance (as measured by their average gross excess returns) is hump-shaped in data miners' search costs (c$c$) and the data frontier (τdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$). Indeed, the improvement in the average quality of asset managers' signals has a positive effect on asset managers' average performance, while the increase in price informativeness has a negative effect (because it reduces each asset manager's informational edge). Whenτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$becomes large enough orc$c$small enough, the second effect dominates. Thus, in the long run, the big data revolution is expected to erode active asset managers' performance (quants and discretionary funds alike). Shocks to the data frontier and data miners' search costs should also affect the dispersion of performance within a group of asset managers (experts or data miners). The average performance of an asset manager increases with the quality of her signal, other things equal. Thus, within a group, the difference between the average performance of top and bottom performers increases in the difference between the quality of their signals. A reduction in data miners' search costs raises the lowest quality of the signals used by both\nI. Contribution to the Literature: Our paper is related to three strands of literature. First, it contributes to the theoretical literature studying trends in the asset management industry (such as the rise of institutional investors, institutional holdings' concentration, or indexing) and their effects (e.g., Huang, Qiu, and Yang (2019), Bond and García (2021), Buss and Sundaresan (2022), and Kacperczyk, Nosal, and Sundaresan (2024)). Here, we focus on the rise of quant funds and relate it to (i) the availability of new data and (ii) a decline in the cost of processing this data. We are not aware of other papers that do so. The theoretical literature on quantitative investors is scarce. Malikov and Pasquariello (2022) introduce a quantitative informed investor to the model of Kyle (1985). This investor is myopic in the sense that her trading strategy is optimal, provided that other informed investors behave as if she was not present. This assumption captures the idea that quantitative investors follow fixed trading rules calibrated on past data (“backtesting”). In contrast, we formalize quants as agents that produce information through a search process and we focus on the effects of both data abundance and information processing costs on their strategies (these parameters play no role in Malikov and Pasquariello (2022)). Our modeling approach is closer to Garleanu and Pedersen (2018). In their model, active asset managers can be either informed or uninformed and they study how investors allocate capital to both types. Investors can identify informed asset managers at a cost. Here, we assume that identifying informed asset managers is costless but we introduce heterogeneity in the technologies used by active asset managers to generate their investment ideas. Second, our paper contributes to the literature on endogenous information acquisition in noisy rational expectations models (see Veldkamp (2011) for a survey). These models assume that either (i) investors can obtain a signal of fixed exogenous precision by paying a cost (e.g., Grossman and Stiglitz (1980)) or (ii) investors choose the precision of their signal, with signals of higher precision being more costly (e.g., Verrecchia (1982)). Neither of these approaches can be used to study how an exogenous shock on the distribution of signals' precision affects agents' efforts to improve the precision of their signals (the intensive margin of information production). Under the first approach, only the extensive margin of information production (the mass of investors acquiring information) is endogenous. Under the second approach, the intensive margin varies endogenously but only through shocks to the cost of information production. Yet, as explained in the introduction, the availability of new data sets enables investors to find signals of higher quality without a change in data processing costs. Thus, to analyze the effects of data abundance on investors' efforts to discover signals of high quality, one needs a new modeling approach. Our methodological contribution is to propose such an approach. Our framework allows us to analyze the effect of exogenous shocks on investors' signals precision (shocks toτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\text{max}}_{dm}$)—holding the cost of information production (c$c$) constant—on both (i) the intensive margin of information production (data miners' search intensity) and (ii) the extensive margin (the allocation of capital between two types of informed investors). In this way, we can untangle the effects of the two dimensions of the big data revolution: (i) a reduction in the cost of processing data and (ii) an increase in the precision of the best signals that investors can obtain due to an expansion of available data. We find that these two shocks can affect efforts to produce information in opposite directions. To our knowledge, this economic insight is new and cannot be delivered by the existing literature (since it does not allow to analyze (ii) separately from (i)). Han and Sangiorgi (2018) and Banerjee and Breon-Drish (2021) also formalize information acquisition as a search problem but they analyze different questions. Han and Sangiorgi (2018) provide a microfoundation for the assumption that information acquisition costs are increasing and convex in precision (e.g., Verrecchia (1982)). In Banerjee and Breon-Drish (2021), one investor optimally alternates between periods in which she searches for information and periods in which she does not. When she searches for information, the investor finds a signal of a given precision according to a Poisson process and starts trading on this signal as soon as she finds it. In this model, investors face uncertainty on forgone trading opportunities (due to search delays) rather than signal quality as in our model. Lastly, our paper contributes to the growing theoretical literature on the effects of new technologies for producing financial information (e.g., Dugast and Foucault (2018), Farboodi and Veldkamp (2020), Milhet (2020), and Huang, Xiong, and Yang (2022)). This literature assumes that information technology progress reduces the cost of processing information (or relaxes investors' attention constraints) and explores ramifications of this assumption. Our model accounts for another dimension of this progress, namely, improvement in the precision of the signals that investors can obtain due to new data (data abundance).\nII. Model: Figure1describes the timing of the model. In period 0, a continuum of investors (of mass one) invest their savings, denoted asW0$W_0$, in the stock market through active asset managers. As in Garleanu and Pedersen (2018), asset managers can hold a risk-free asset (whose rate of return is normalized to zero) and a risky asset. The payoff of the risky asset,ω$\\omega$, is realized in period 3 and is normally distributed with mean zero and varianceσω2$\\sigma _{\\omega }^2$. There are two types of asset managers: (i) experts (a continuum of mass one) or (ii) data miners (a continuum of mass one). Each asset manager can serve only one investor, so there is one fund of each type per capita (we relax this assumption in SectionVI.B). We denote byμ$\\mu$(1−μ)$(1-\\mu)$the fraction of investors who allocate capital to data miners (experts). Henceforth, subscript “dm$dm$” refers to data miners and subscript “ex$ex$” to expert. We interpret experts as asset managers relying on judgmental analysis to generate investment ideas (so-called discretionary investors) and data miners as managers relying on a quantitative approach to obtain trading signals (quant funds). As explained in the introduction, a central task of these funds is discovering new predictors of asset payoffs (see Narang (2013), Chapters 8 and 9). Data miners' search costc$c$is the cost of performing this task. This cost has declined over time because of digitization (which enables automation of unstructured data processing) and improvements in computing power (which enables research teams to complete exploration rounds more quickly). The data frontier,τdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$, captures a different dimension of the big data revolution, namely, the proliferation of new data sets (so-called alternative data). As more data sets become available (data abundance), data miners can use more diverse variables to predict asset payoffs. Combined with progress in forecasting techniques, this evolution pushes back the data frontier (increasesτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$). A predictor can be viewed as a function (e.g., fitted with linear regressions or ML techniques) of variables from different data sets (e.g., accounting data, geolocation data, and consumer transactions data) that minimizes the predictor's average forecasting error in-sample. The data miner then uses the realization of these variables in period 2 (out-of-sample) to obtain her signal,sτ$s_{\\tau }$.10We formalize this interpretation in SectionII.Cof theInternet Appendixwhere we assume that data miners obtain a predictor in each round by running a regression ofω$\\omega$on afixednumber,N$N$, of variables.11The predictive power of one (or several) new variable used in place of one (or several) variable used in former exploration rounds is random. For this reason, as assumed in our model, the quality of a predictor obtained in a given round is random and can drop from one round to the next.12 To summarize, we interpret an increase inτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$as reflecting the availability of new data sets, while a decrease inc$c$captures the diminishing costs of information processing due to greater computing power. Our analysis focuses on equilibrium effects of shocks to these parameters. The market for the risky asset opens in period 2 after all data miners find a predictor with satisficing quality (i.e., with quality aboveτi∗$\\tau _i^*$). At the beginning of period 2, after observing her or his signalsτ$s_{\\tau }$, each asset manager with capital chooses a trading strategy, that is, a demand schedule,xi(sτ,p)$x_i(s_{\\tau },p)$, wherep$p$is the price of the risky asset. We assume that investors observe the skill,τ$\\tau$, of each expert and correctly anticipate data miners' stopping rules in equilibrium (hence, they knowH(τi)$H(\\tau _i)$andV(τi∗)$V(\\tau _i^*)$). We also assume that investors have no expertise and so no ability to obtain an informative signal. It is therefore never optimal for them to directly invest in the risky asset since its expected risk premium, conditional on public information, is zero.14 Using this observation, in the next section, we solve the equilibrium in the following way. We conjecture that, in equilibrium, the quality of the marginal expert,τ̲$\\underline{\\tau }$, is identical to the quality of the data miner with the worst predictor,τ∗$\\tau ^*$, so thatμ∗=Γ(τ∗)$\\mu ^*=\\Gamma (\\tau ^*)$(Equation (8)).18In a first step (Proposition1), we solve for the equilibrium of the trading stage in period 2 takingτ∗$\\tau ^*$(and thereforeμ∗$\\mu ^*$) as given. From this step, we then derive data miners' optimal search intensity,τ∗$\\tau ^*$(Proposition2). Finally, we show that in equilibrium, it must be the case thatτ̲=τ∗$\\underline{\\tau }=\\tau ^*$and thereforeμ∗=Γ(τ∗)$\\mu ^*=\\Gamma (\\tau ^*)$, as conjectured (Proposition3).\nIII. Equilibrium of the Financial Market: Proposition 1.In equilibrium, an asset manager's demand for the risky asset is An asset manager's optimal holding of the risky asset is proportional to the difference between her signal (sτ$s_{\\tau }$) and the price of the asset (p$p$). Holding this difference constant, asset managers with signals of higher quality (largerτ$\\tau$) take larger positions (β(τ)$\\beta (\\tau)$is larger) because, conditional on their information, their residual uncertainty about the payoff of the asset is smaller. Thus,β(τ)$\\beta (\\tau)$measures the aggressiveness with which an asset manager exploits her signal. Lemma 1.Other things equal, the average quality of asset managers' signals,τ¯(τ∗;τdmmax)$\\bar{\\tau }(\\tau ^*;\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm})$, and therefore, price informativeness,I(τ∗;τdmmax)$\\mathcal {I}(\\tau ^*;\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm})$, increases with data miners' search intensityτ∗$\\tau ^*$. Lemma 2.In equilibrium, the trading value of a signal with typeτ$\\tau$is The trading value of a signal increases with its quality and decreases with price informativeness. Thus, it is inversely related to the average quality of asset managers' signals. Hence, holding quality constant, the value of a signal for a data miner (or expert) is smaller if other data miners are more demanding with respect to the quality of their predictors (i.e.,τ∗$\\tau ^*$is larger). Proposition 2.In equilibrium, data miners' search intensity,τ∗$\\tau ^*$, is the unique solution to Equation (21). It is always strictly smaller thanτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$and it is bounded above byΨ−1(exp(−ρc))$\\Psi ^{-1}(\\exp (-\\rho c))$for all values ofτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$. Moreover, it is strictly larger than zero if and only ifF(0)<exp(−ρc)$F(0) < \\exp (-\\rho c)$. Intuitively, whenexp(−ρc)≤F(0)$\\exp (-\\rho c) \\le F(0)$(i.e., whenc$c$is large), the expected utility cost of exploration is larger than expected utility of trading for a data miner. Hence, in this case, data miners do not search (τ∗=0$\\tau ^*=0$). In equilibrium, data miners' continuation value of search does not depend on the number of completed search rounds (see Equation (18)). Thus, the ex-ante expected utility of investors who allocate capital to data miners isV(τ∗)=J(τ∗,τ∗)$V(\\tau ^*)=J(\\tau ^*,\\tau ^*)$. The ex-ante expected utility of an investor who allocates capital to an expert with skillτ$\\tau$isH(τ)=g(τ,τ∗)$H(\\tau)=g(\\tau,\\tau ^*)$, which strictly increases withτ$\\tau$(Lemma2). Investors must optimally allocate (i) capital to all experts that deliver an expected utility larger than the expected utility they can obtain with data miners and (ii) no capital to other experts. Consequently, asH(τ)$H(\\tau)$strictly increases withτ$\\tau$, in an interior equilibrium (i.e.,0<μ∗<1$0 < \\mu ^*<1$), the skill of the marginal expert (the expert with the lowest skill among those receiving capital),τ̲$\\underline{\\tau }$, must be such thatH(τ̲)=V(τ∗)$H(\\underline{\\tau })=V(\\tau ^*)$.19Now, recall that, in equilibrium, data miners' optimal search intensity is such thatJ(τ∗,τ∗)=g(τ∗,τ∗)$J(\\tau ^*,\\tau ^*)= g(\\tau ^*,\\tau ^*)$(see Equation (20)). Therefore, the conditionH(τ̲)=V(τ∗)$H(\\underline{\\tau })=V(\\tau ^*)$imposesg(τ̲,τ∗)=g(τ∗,τ∗)$g(\\underline{\\tau },\\tau ^*)=g(\\tau ^*,\\tau ^*)$, which means thatτ̲=τ∗$\\underline{\\tau }=\\tau ^*$. Thus, in equilibrium, the skill of the marginal expert,τ̲$\\underline{\\tau }$, must be equal toτ∗$\\tau ^*$and thereforeμ∗=Γ(τ∗)$\\mu ^*=\\Gamma (\\tau ^*)$(Equation (8)), as conjectured. Proposition 3.SupposeF(0)<exp(−ρc)<F(τexmax)$F(0) < \\exp (-\\rho c) < F({\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{ex}})$. In equilibrium, the skill of the marginal expert isτ̲=τ∗$\\underline{\\tau }= \\tau ^*$, whereτ∗$\\tau ^*$solves Equation (21) and0<τ∗<τexmax$0 < \\tau ^* < {\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{ex}}$. Hence, the allocation of capital between data miners and experts is such thatμ∗=Γ(τ∗)$\\mu ^*=\\Gamma (\\tau ^*)$with0<μ∗<1$0 < \\mu ^* < 1$, so that both data miners and experts receive capital. Last, the variablesx∗$x^*$andp∗$p^*$are given as in Proposition1. Proposition3provides a full characterization of the equilibrium of the financial market when both experts and data miners receive capital in equilibrium, that is,0<μ∗<1$0 < \\mu ^* <1$. This condition is satisfied if and only ifF(0)<exp(−ρc)<F(τexmax)$F(0) < \\exp (-\\rho c) < F({\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{ex}})$. Otherwise, we obtain a corner equilibrium in which investors allocate capital to experts only (μ∗=0$\\mu ^*=0$whenexp(−ρc)<F(0)$\\exp (-\\rho c)< F(0)$) or to data miners only (μ∗=1$\\mu ^*=1$whenexp(−ρc)>F(τexmax)$\\exp (-\\rho c) > F({\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{ex}})$). In the rest of the paper, we focus on the case in whichF(0)<exp(−ρc)<F(τexmax)$F(0) < \\exp (-\\rho c) < F({\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{ex}})$so that the equilibrium is interior (corner cases are less interesting and can always be avoided by settingc$c$small enough andτexmax${\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{ex}}$large enough).\nIV. Capital Allocation: Data Miners versus Experts: In this section, we study how a reduction in data miners' search costs (c$c$) or a push back of the data frontier (an increase inτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$) affect data miners' search intensity (τ∗$\\tau ^*$), the allocation of capital to data miners relative to experts (μ∗$\\mu ^*$), the average quality of asset managers' signals (τ¯$\\bar{\\tau }$), and price informativeness (I$\\cal {I}$). We are particularly interested in the effects that arise when the cost of search becomes very small or data become very abundant (τdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$very large), as these limiting cases are often described as the endpoint of current progress in information technology (Nordhaus (2021)). Proposition 4.A decrease in data miners' search costs,c$c$, always increases data miners' search intensityτ∗$\\tau ^*$in equilibrium (∂τ∗/∂c<0$\\partial \\tau ^*/\\partial c < 0$), andτ∗$\\tau ^*$goes toτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$whenc$c$goes to zero. For this reason, a decrease in data miners' search costs raises the allocation capital to data miners (μ∗$\\mu ^*$). Moreover, it increases (i) the average quality of data miners and experts' signals (τ¯dm${\\bar{\\tau }_{dm}}$andτ¯ex${\\bar{\\tau }_{ex}}$), (ii) the average quality of all asset managers' signals (τ¯$\\bar{\\tau }$), and, in turn, (iii) price informativeness (I$\\mathcal {I}$). Holdingτ∗$\\tau ^*$constant, a decrease in data miners' search costs directly reduces the expected utility cost of launching a new round of exploration after finding a predictor (the first term in bracket in Equation (18)) for data miners. Hence, it raises the value of searching for another predictor after finding one, other things equal. Data miners therefore become more demanding with respect to the quality of their predictor in equilibrium andτ∗$\\tau ^*$increases. As a result, data miners deliver higher ex-ante expected utility to investors (V(τ∗)=g(τ∗,τ∗)$V(\\tau ^*)=g(\\tau ^*,\\tau ^*)$increases). Consequently, investors allocate more capital to data miners (μ∗$\\mu ^*$increases) and the quality of the marginal expert increases. These effects raise the average quality of the signals used by both data miners and experts and therefore price informativeness (see Equation (14)). The latter effect reduces the trading value of their signals for all asset managers (see Equation (16)). Hence, it dampens the direct positive effect of a decrease in data miners' search costs,c$c$, on the value of data miners' search for a better predictor. However, in equilibrium, this indirect effect never fully offsets the positive direct effect of a decrease inc$c$on the value of searching for another predictor after obtaining one.20 In the next proposition, we describe the effect of the data frontier,τdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$, on the equilibrium. For the proof of this proposition, we need the following (mild) technical assumption. Assumption 1.The densityψ(.)$\\psi (.)$(defined in Equation (2)), is such thatlimτ→∞∫0ττ′ψ(τ′)dτ′$\\lim _{\\tau \\rightarrow \\infty } \\int _{0}^{\\tau } \\tau ^{\\prime } \\psi (\\tau ^{\\prime }) d\\tau ^{\\prime }$exists and is finite.21 Proposition 5.Under Assumption1, there exists a thresholdτtr(c)$\\tau ^{tr}(c)$such that whenτdmmax≥τtr(c)$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}\\ge \\tau ^{tr}(c)$a push back of the data frontier reduces (i) data miners' search intensity,τ∗$\\tau ^*$(∂τ∗/∂τdmmax<0$\\partial \\tau ^*/\\partial \\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}<0$) and (ii) the allocation of capital to data miners (∂μ∗/∂τdmmax<0$\\partial \\mu ^*/\\partial \\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}<0$). In this case, data abundance reduces the average quality of experts' signals (τ¯ex${\\bar{\\tau }_{ex}}$) while it increases the average quality of data miners' signals (τ¯dm${\\bar{\\tau }_{dm}}$). In any case, the average quality of asset managers' signals (τ¯$\\bar{\\tau }$), and therefore price informativeness, (I$\\mathcal {I}$) increase withτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$. However, price informativeness remains bounded from above whenτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$goes to infinity. Thus, in contrast to a reduction in search costs, a push back of the data frontier can induce data miners to becomelessdemanding with respect to the quality of their predictors, leading investors to shift capital from data miners to experts. The gold nugget effect is bounded byϕ∗(τdmmax)$\\phi ^*(\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm})$, even whenτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$becomes large. Indeed, the expected utility gain of finding a predictor is bounded since investors' expected utility is concave (g(τ,τ∗)∈(−1,0)$g(\\tau,\\tau ^*) \\in (-1,0)$in our setup; see Equation (16)). In contrast, the effect of data abundance on price informativeness (∂I∂τdmmax$\\frac{\\partial \\cal {I} }{\\partial \\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}}$) is of the order ofϕ∗(τdmmax)×τdmmax$\\phi ^*(\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}) \\times \\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$(up to a scaling factor) whenτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$becomes large (see Equation (24)), so that the sum of the gold nugget and the price informativeness effects becomes proportional to the conditional probability of finding the best predictor,ϕ∗(τdmmax)$\\phi ^*(\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm})$, with a factor of the order of1+Eϕ∂g(τ,τ∗)∂Iτ∗≤τ≤τdmmaxτdmmax$1+\\operatorname{\\mathsf {E}}_{\\phi }\\left[\\left.\\frac{\\partial g(\\tau,\\tau ^*) }{\\partial \\cal {I}}\\right| \\tau ^* \\le \\tau \\le \\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}\\right] \\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$. This factor is negative forτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$large sinceEϕ∂g(τ,τ∗)∂Iτ∗≤τ≤τdmmax$\\operatorname{\\mathsf {E}}_{\\phi }\\left[\\left.\\frac{\\partial g(\\tau,\\tau ^*)}{\\partial \\cal {I}}\\right| \\tau ^* \\le \\tau \\le \\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}\\right]$remains strictly negative even whenτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$goes to infinity as price informativeness is bounded above (Proposition5). Thus, the informativeness effect dominates the gold nugget effect whenτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$is large enough. Therefore, there is always a threshold,τtr(c)$\\tau ^{tr}(c)$, such that data miners' search intensity decreases with data abundance whenτdmmax>τtr(c)$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}> \\tau ^{tr}(c)$. As data miners become less demanding with respect to the quality of their predictors, they deliver smaller expected utility to investors. In this case, a push back of the data frontier triggers a reallocation of investors' capital from data miners to experts (μ∗$\\mu ^*$drops) until the point at which the skill of the marginal expert is identical to the quality of the worst signal for data miners (τ∗$\\tau ^*$). Thus, forτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$large enough, a push back of the data frontier indirectly reduces experts' average skill (τ¯ex${\\bar{\\tau }_{ex}}$). Interestingly, even though a push back of the data frontier can reduce data miners' search intensity, it always raises the average precision of all asset managers' signals and therefore price informativeness. Intuitively, if this were not the case, then the price informativeness effect would work in the same direction as the gold nugget effect. It would make searching for a signal of high quality more desirable (the second term in Equation (25) would be positive), giving a contradiction. Whenτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$is small enough, the effects of an increase inτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$onτ∗$\\tau ^*$andμ∗$\\mu ^*$are reversed (the gold nugget effect dominates the price informativeness effect). Hence, in equilibrium, data miners' search intensityτ∗$\\tau ^*$and the fraction of capital allocated to data miners,μ∗$\\mu ^*$, are therefore hump-shaped functions of the data frontier,τdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$. Figure2illustrates this point when the cumulative distribution of predictors' quality isΦ(τ)=1−(1+τ)−3/21−(1+τdmmax)−3/2$\\Phi (\\tau)=\\frac{1-(1+\\tau)^{-3/2}}{1-(1+\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm})^{-3/2}}$.23A push back of the data frontier (lower panel in Figure2) initially triggers an increase in the allocation of capital to data miners. However, at some point (whenτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$exceeds the thresholdτtr(c)$\\tau ^{tr}(c)$), this trend reverses and capital flows back to experts. Proposition 6.In equilibrium, an increase in the volume of noise tradingση2$\\sigma _{\\eta }^2$or in the volatility of the asset payoffσω2$\\sigma _{\\omega }^2$triggers (i) a decrease in price informativeness (I$\\mathcal {I}$), (ii) an increase in data miners' search intensity (τ∗$\\tau ^*$), (iii) an increase in the allocation of capital (μ∗$\\mu ^*$) to data miners, (iv) an improvement in the average quality of data miners' signals (τ¯dm${\\bar{\\tau }_{dm}}$) and in the average quality of experts' signals (τ¯ex${\\bar{\\tau }_{ex}}$), and (v) an improvement in the average quality of all asset managers' signals (τ¯$\\bar{\\tau }$). Other things equal, an increase in the volume of noise trading or the volatility of the asset reduces the informativeness of the equilibrium price. This effect raises the expected value of trading. Thus, the value to data miners of searching for a predictor increases and they therefore become more demanding with respect to their predictors (τ∗$\\tau ^*$increases). As a result, data miners attract relatively more capital (μ∗$\\mu ^*$increases). This raises the quality of the marginal expert, and therefore, ultimately, the average quality of all asset managers. One implication is that quant funds should attract more capital in periods of high volatility. Furthermore, dispersion in their performance should decline during periods of high volatility (an increase inτ∗$\\tau ^*$reduces dispersion in data miners' performance; see SectionV.B).\nV. Progress in Information Technology and Performance in Active Management: We now study how the data frontier and data miners' search costs affect (i) the average performance of all asset managers, (ii) the dispersion in performance across asset managers of a given type, and (iii) the performance of data miners relative to experts. These questions are of broad interest given the substantial literature on active asset managers' performance (see, e.g., Berk and van Binsbergen (2015), Pastor, Stambaugh, and Taylor (2015), Zhu (2018), Gerakos, Linnainmaa, and Morse (2021), and Barras, Gagliardini, and Scaillet (2022) for recent empirical studies). Corollary 1.Denote byτ¯0≡τ¯ex(0)$\\bar{\\tau }_0 \\equiv \\bar{\\tau }_{ex}(0)$the average predictor's quality in the absence of data miners (i.e.,μ∗=0$\\mu ^* =0$). As explained previously, the big data revolution reduces quant funds' search costsc$c$and pushes back the data frontierτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$. According to Corollary1, this evolution should first raise the average performance of asset managers and then reduce it (see Figure3). Intuitively, in the long run, the positive effect of a decrease inc$c$or an increase inτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$on price informativeness dominates, so that the average performance of asset managers drops. This implication is related to Stambaugh (2020) (see his Proposition 5 and Figure 5), who shows that improvements in the skills of active asset managers can reduce their average performance. One important difference between his model and ours is that we explicitly relate changes in asset managers' skills to shocks to the cost of search for data miners or the data frontier. Barras, Gagliardini, and Scaillet (2022) and Pastor, Stambaugh, and Taylor (2015) find substantial dispersion in performance (as measured by funds' alphas on the first dollar invested) across active equity funds.27This finding is consistent with our model in which asset managers differ in their skill (τ$\\tau$) and therefore their average performance (R¯e(τ)$\\bar{R}^e(\\tau)$). In our theory, the dispersion in managers' skills and in turn performance is endogenous and determined by data miners' search intensity (τ∗$\\tau ^*$). Thus, shocks to the data frontier and data miners' search costs also affect the dispersion in asset managers' performance within fund groups (data miners and experts). Corollary 2. These implications follow directly from the fact that shocks to computing power and data abundance affect data miners' search intensity,τ∗$\\tau ^*$, in opposite directions whenτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$is large enough (Propositions4and5). Corollary 3.Whenτexmax<∞${\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{ex}}< \\infty$andα$\\alpha$is large enough, then: Corollary 4.Whenτdmmax≥τtr(c)$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}\\ge \\tau ^{tr}(c)$, the average performance of data miners relative to experts increases withτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$. This result is a direct consequence of Proposition5. Whenτdmmax≥τtr(c)$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}\\ge \\tau ^{tr}(c)$, a push back of the data frontier,τdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$, improves the average quality of data miners' signals (τ¯dm${\\bar{\\tau }_{dm}}$) but reduces the average quality of experts' signals (τ¯ex${\\bar{\\tau }_{ex}}$) because investors allocate more capital to experts (and therefore the quality of the marginal expert drops). It follows that data miners' relative performance improves (the condition thatτdmmax≥τtr(c)$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}\\ge \\tau ^{tr}(c)$is sufficient but not necessary for this implication; see Figure5). In contrast, a decrease in data miners' search cost,c$c$, improves the average quality of the signals used by both groups of asset managers (Proposition4). Thus, its effect on data miners' relative performance is less clear and one cannot sign it without additional assumptions on the distribution of experts' signal quality (Γ(.)$\\Gamma (.)$). Under the restrictive assumption that this distribution is similar to the distribution of data miners' signal quality (in the sense thatΓ(τ)=Ψ(τ)/Ψ(τexmax)$\\Gamma (\\tau) = \\Psi (\\tau)/\\Psi ({\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{ex}})$), we obtain the following result. Corollary 5.Suppose thatΓ(τ)=Ψ(τ)/Ψ(τexmax)$\\Gamma (\\tau) = \\Psi (\\tau)/\\Psi ({\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{ex}})$. Whenτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$andτexmax${\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{ex}}$are high enough, the average performance of data miners relative to experts decreases when data miners' search cost,c$c$, decreases if and only ifτexmax>τdmmax${\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{ex}}> \\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$. Figure5illustrates the results in this section. For the parameter values considered in Figure5, data miners perform better on average than experts (RP>0$RP >0$). Data miners' relative performance improves when the data frontier (τdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$) increases and worsens when data miners' search cost is reduced. This again shows that the effects of a reduction inc$c$and an increase inτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$are not the same. For this figure, we do not assume thatΓ(τ)=Ψ(τ)/Ψ(τexmax)$\\Gamma (\\tau) = \\Psi (\\tau)/\\Psi ({\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{ex}})$and yet the pattern predicted by Corollary5applies (the condition in Corollary5is sufficient but not necessary).\nVI. Extensions: Asw(τ)$w(\\tau)$increases withτ$\\tau$, investors' rankings of asset managers after accounting for fees is the same for all values ofκ<1$\\kappa <1$. Thus, the allocation of capital between data miners and experts is as in the baseline model (κ=0$\\kappa =0$). Therefore, the equilibrium described in Proposition3(and therefore all of the implications of the model) still holds whenκ<1$\\kappa <1$.31 Interestingly, experts' fees depend on data miners' search intensity. Other things equal, an increase in data miners' search intensity triggers a drop in the allocation of capital to experts and hence should reduce their fees. We obtain the following corollary (see Figure6for an illustration). Corollary 6.Experts' fees decline when data miners' search cost,c$c$, decreases. They also decline following an increase in the data frontier,τdmmax$\\tau ^{max}_{dm}$, if this increase raises data miners' search intensity. When it does not, the fees charged by experts with low skill (τ$\\tau$close enough toτ∗$\\tau ^*$) increase withτdmmax$\\tau ^{max}_{dm}$. When data miners' search costs decline, price informativeness increases. This effect reduces investors' certainty equivalents with data miners and experts (w(τ)$w(\\tau)$andw(τ∗)$w(\\tau ^*)$). However, this reduction is smaller for data miners because the decrease in search costs induces them to search more intensively (τ∗$\\tau ^*$increases). Thus, allocating capital to data miners becomes relatively more attractive (wo∗=w(τ∗)$w_o^*=w(\\tau ^*)$rises) and experts must decrease their fees. The same effects play out when an increase in the data frontier,τdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$, raises data miners' search intensity. However, when it does not (τdmmax≥τtr(c)$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}\\ge \\tau ^{tr}(c)$), the effects are reversed: A push back of the data frontier reduces data miners' search intensity and, in turn, the certainty equivalent of investors' expected utility with data miners (their outside option). Thus, the net effect of raisingτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$on experts' fees is ambiguous: it lowers investors' outside option (wo∗$w_o^*$) (a positive effect on experts' fees), but it also increases price informativeness (a negative effect). For experts with relatively low skills (those withτ$\\tau$close to the marginal expert), the first effect dominates so that their fees increase (Corollary6). For highly skilled experts, numerical simulations suggest that enhanced price informativeness is the dominating force and thus their fees always drop whenτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$increases (we have not been able to prove this result analytically). Proposition 7.Letτ̂(A¯ex)≡Γ−1(A¯ex−1A¯ex)$\\hat{\\tau }(\\bar{A}_{ex}) \\equiv \\Gamma ^{-1}(\\frac{\\bar{A}_{ex}-1}{\\bar{A}_{ex}})$. SupposeF(τ̂(A¯ex))<exp(−ρc(A¯dm))<F(τexmax)$F(\\hat{\\tau }(\\bar{A}_{ex})) < \\exp (-\\rho c(\\bar{A}_{dm})) < F({\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{ex}})$. In equilibrium,τ∗$\\tau ^*$solvesF(τ∗)=exp(−ρc(A¯dm))$F(\\tau ^*) = \\exp (-\\rho c(\\bar{A}_{dm}))$, whereF(.)$F(.)$is given by Equation (21) and the skill of the marginal expert isτ̲=τ∗$\\underline{\\tau }= \\tau ^*$, withτ̂(A¯ex)<τ∗<τexmax$\\hat{\\tau }(\\bar{A}_{ex}) < \\tau ^* < {\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{ex}}$. Hence, the allocation of capital between data miners and experts is such thatμ∗=(1−A¯ex)+A¯exΓ(τ∗)$\\mu ^*=(1-\\bar{A}_{ex})+\\bar{A}_{ex} \\Gamma (\\tau ^*)$, with0<μ∗<1$0 < \\mu ^* < 1$, so that both data miners and experts receive capital. Experts with skill aboveτ∗$\\tau ^*$have a sizeAex∗=A¯ex$A_{ex}^*=\\bar{A}_{ex}$and data miners who receive capital have sizeAdm∗=A¯dm$A_{dm}^*=\\bar{A}_{dm}$. Thus, a fractionμ∗/A¯dm$\\mu ^*/\\bar{A}_{dm}$of all data miners are active. Finally,x∗$x^*$andp∗$p^*$are given as in Proposition1. The rest of the analysis is as in the baseline model because data miners' search intensity,τ∗$\\tau ^*$, is determined by the same condition, that is,F(τ∗)=exp(−ρc(A¯dm))$F(\\tau ^*)=\\exp (-\\rho c(\\bar{A}_{dm}))$. Consequently, all results still hold as they follow from this condition. In addition, an increase in data miners' capacity,A¯dm$\\bar{A}_{dm}$, has the same effects as a decrease in data miners' search costs because the role ofc$c$in the baseline analysis is now played byc(A¯dm)=cA¯dm$c(\\bar{A}_{dm})=\\frac{c}{\\bar{A}_{dm}}$. Thus, data miners' search intensity and in turn price informativeness increase with data miners' capacity (Proposition4). In addition, an increase in data miners' capacity reduces the dispersion in performance within each group of asset managers (Corollary3) and experts' fees drop when data miners' size increases (Corollary6). AsF(τ̂(A¯ex))$F(\\hat{\\tau }(\\bar{A}_{ex}))$increases withA¯ex$\\bar{A}_{ex}$, the conditionF(τ̂(A¯ex))<exp(−ρc(A¯dm))$F(\\hat{\\tau }(\\bar{A}_{ex})) < \\exp (-\\rho c(\\bar{A}_{dm}))$(i.e.,μ∗>0$\\mu ^*>0$) requires experts' capacity,A¯ex$\\bar{A}_{ex}$, to be superiorly bounded (the bound increases with data miners' capacity sincec(A¯dm)$c(\\bar{A}_{dm})$decreases withA¯dm$\\bar{A}_{dm}$). Otherwise, the best experts attract all investors' capital since they deliver a higher certainty equivalent to investors (w(τ$w(\\tau$) increases withτ$\\tau$). Thus, for data miners to be active, experts must be in scarce supply, that is, their capacity cannot be too large. In reality, funds face decreasing returns to scale, due, for instance, to organizational costs (see Chen et al. (2004) for evidence), which incentivizes them to limit their size (capacity). For instance, suppose that funds choose their capacityA¯$\\bar{A}$(i.e., the maximum number of clients that a fund is willing to serve) in period 0 to maximize their fee revenues net of costCj(A¯)$C_j(\\bar{A})$(j∈{ex,dm}$j \\in \\lbrace ex,dm\\rbrace$), which is increasing and convex in the capacity of the fund. WhenCj(A¯)$C_j(\\bar{A})$is zero forA¯≤A¯j$\\bar{A} \\le \\bar{A}_j$and infinite forA¯>A¯j$\\bar{A} > \\bar{A}_j$, experts (data miners) optimally choose a capacity equal toA¯ex$\\bar{A}_{ex}$(respectively,A¯dm$\\bar{A}_{dm}$), as we assume so far (see SectionII.E.1in theInternet Appendix). For less extreme decreasing returns to scale, funds would also optimally limit their capacity. However, the derivation of the equilibrium is significantly more complex because in this case, experts with different levels of skill choose different capacities. As explained in SectionII.E.2of theInternet Appendix, this feature makes solving (even numerically) for the equilibrium with endogenous capacities significantly more difficult. Finally, in the model, the aggregate size of the active asset management industry (its total AUM) is determined by the mass of investors,K$K$. In the baseline model,K=1$K=1$. It is straightforward to relax this assumption. In this case, the previous analysis is unchanged, except that (i) funds' size must be defined asA¯j/K$\\bar{A}_{j}/K$forj∈{ex,dm}$j \\in \\lbrace ex,dm\\rbrace$(intuitively what matters is funds' relative capacity) and (ii) in the expression for price informativeness (Equation (14)),ρ$\\rho$must be replaced byρ/K$\\rho /K$(see SectionII.E.2in theInternet Appendix). Hence, price informativeness increases with the size (K$K$) of the asset management industry and, as a result, asset managers' performance is negatively related to industry size (see Equations (29) and (30)), as found empirically by Pastor, Stambaugh, and Taylor (2015).\nVII. Empirical Implications: The last 20 years have witnessed tremendous advances in information technology, with a sharp decline in computing costs (enabling the use of machine learning techniques) and steady growth of so-called alternative data sets (such as social media data, credit card data, and satellite imagery).32In our model, this evolution corresponds to a decrease in data miners' information processing costs (c$c$) and a push back of the data frontier (τdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$). TableIsummarizes the implications of our model regarding the effects of these parameters. A first implication is that this trend (the decline inc$c$and the increase inτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$) should increase the capital allocated to quants (data miners in our model) relative to discretionary funds, provided thatτdmmax≤τtr(c)$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}\\le \\tau ^{tr}(c)$(Propositions4and5). This is consistent with the rise of quant funds since the turn of the millennium (see Harvey et al. (2017), Abis (2022), and Dyer, Guest, and Yu (2022)). Another implication is that the decline in information processing costs and data abundance should trigger an improvement in price informativeness (I$\\cal {I}$). Consistent with this implication, Zhu (2019) finds that the availability of satellite imagery and consumer-browsing data—a positive shock toτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$—improves price informativeness for the stocks covered by such data (see also Bonelli and Foucault (2023)). An additional implication, yet untested, is that this improvement should be due to an increase in the average quality of active asset managers' signals (even though the dispersion in quality could increase).33 A decrease in information processing costs (c$c$) or a push back of the data frontier (τdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$) can also reduce the (cross-sectional) average performance of all active asset managers (see Corollary1and Figure3). In line with this implication, Bonelli and Foucault (2023) find that the availability of satellite imagery data reduces active funds' average excess returns in stocks covered by these data (U.S. retailers' stocks). These findings provide only suggestive (and fragmentary) evidence consistent with the model. Literature on the effects of big data on active asset managers is still scarce. Tests of our theory should focus on its most novel predictions, namely, (i) the availability of new data can trigger a decline in the capital allocated to quant funds and reduce the difference between the performance of top and bottom performers in a given group of funds (data miners or quants), while (ii) a drop inc$c$should have the opposite effects (see Corollary3and Figure4). For these tests, empiricists could (i) classify active funds into quants and discretionary funds, using, for instance, methodologies and data similar to those used by Harvey et al. (2017), Abis (2022), and Dyer, Guest, and Yu (2022) and (ii) exploit natural experiments that increase the amount of available data (raiseτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$) or reduce information processing costs (c$c$). We give examples of such experiments below. The availability of alternative data sets varies across industries and asset classes (see Kolanovic and Smith (2019) and SectionIV.Cin Dessaint, Foucault, and Frésard (2024)). For example, there are far more alternative data sets covering firms in the consumer industry than in health care or covering equity than commodities. As a result, quant funds are differentially exposed to the rise of alternative data sets. Empiricists could exploit this feature to test whether, consistent with our predictions, variation in funds' exposure to alternative data (due to heterogeneity in their holdings) explains (i) the dispersion in funds' performance within a given group (e.g., quant funds) and (ii) the allocation of capital between quant funds and discretionary funds operating in the same industry or asset class. With this approach, identification of the effects of data abundance on the variables of interest (e.g., the dispersion in funds' performance) would come from cross-sectional variations in funds' exposure to alternative data (shocks toτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$).34 For shocks toc$c$, empiricists could use technological changes that reduce the cost of data processing, such as the introduction of cloud computing by Amazon with its release of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2006 (see Ewens, Nanda, and Rhodes-Kropf (2018)) or the Securities and Exchange Commission's 2009 eXtensible Business Reporting Language (XBLR) mandate. The XBLR mandate requires firms to provide their regulatory filings in machine-readable form (through the EDGAR website). It did not change the information content of regulatory filings (firms had to provide the same data before and after the mandate) and thus did not changeτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$. However, it reduced the cost of automated data processing (e.g., using Natural Language Processing techniques; see Bhattacharya, Cho, and Kim (2018) and Zhao (2021)) and thereforec$c$(quantitative funds rely on information in regulatory filings; see Barbopoulos et al. (2021) for evidence). As the introduction of the XBLR mandate was staggered, funds were differentially exposed to it, depending on their holdings. Thus, the XBLR mandate offers another way to study the effect of a reduction in information processing costs for quant funds, holding available data constant.35\nVIII. Conclusion: We study theoretically the effects of the big data revolution on the production of information by active asset managers, their performance, and asset price informativeness. Our model features two types of asset managers, namely, experts (which we interpret as discretionary funds) and data miners (which we interpret as quant funds). Experts have fixed ability to generate trading signals of a given precision about a risky asset, while data miners obtain trading signals through a search process with the goal of discovering the best (i.e., highest-precision) trading signals. We assume that the big data revolution reduces data miners' search costs and enables them to increase the precision of the best signals (the data frontier). We study in detail how these changes affect, in equilibrium, (i) data miners' optimal search strategy, (ii) the allocation of capital between data miners and experts, (iii) asset price informativeness, (iv) asset managers' average performance, (v) the cross-sectional dispersion in asset managers' performance, and (vi) asset managers' fees. This analysis offers a framework to interpret how the rise of quant funds relates to recent advances in information technology and its consequences for price informativeness and active asset managers' performance. Importantly, the model allows us to separately analyze the effects of reducing data miners' costs (e.g., due to greater computing power) and the effects of the data frontier being pushed back (due to new data availability). We show that these two distinct dimensions of the big data revolution do not necessarily have the same implications. For instance, the capital allocated to data miners always rises with a decline in their search costs, while it is a hump-shaped function of the data frontier. This highlights the importance of distinguishing shocks that affect information processing costs from shocks that affect the amount of available data in empirical analyses of the effects of the big data revolution on financial markets. Editors: Stefan Nagel, Philip Bond, Amit Seru, and Wei Xiong\nAppendix: Proof of Proposition 1.We show thatx∗(sτ,p)$x^*(s_{\\tau },p)$andp∗$p^*$as given by Equation (11) and Equation (12) form an equilibrium. First, suppose thatx∗(sτ,p)$x^*(s_{\\tau },p)$is given byx∗(sτ,p)=β(τ)(sτ−p)$x^*(s_{\\tau },p)=\\beta (\\tau) (s_{\\tau } -p)$. In this case, the aggregate demand for the risky asset is given by Now consider asset managers. Using standard calculations in the CARA gaussian framework, we obtain that the optimal demand for the risky asset of an asset manager with signalsτ$s_{\\tau }$is In sum, we have shown that (i) if dealers expect asset managers to follow the trading strategyx∗(sτ,p)$x^*(s_{\\tau },p)$given by Equation (11), then they set a price given by Equation (12) and (ii) if dealers set a price given by Equation (12), then asset managers follow the trading strategyx∗(sτ,p)$x^*(s_{\\tau },p)$given by Equation (11). Thus, the trading strategies and the equilibrium given in Equations (11) and (12) form an equilibrium. It is possible to show that this is the unique equilibrium in which asset managers' trading strategy is a linear function of their signal and the price. Proof of Lemma 1.Using Equation (10) and the factμ∗=Γ(τ∗)$\\mu ^*=\\Gamma (\\tau ^*)$, we obtain Proof of Lemma 2.As in the proof of Proposition1, we defineθω≡1/σω2$\\theta _{\\omega } \\equiv 1/\\sigma _{\\omega }^2$, the precision of asset managers' prior about the asset payoffω$\\omega$, andθξ≡β¯2/ση2$\\theta _{\\xi } \\equiv \\bar{\\beta }^2/\\sigma _{\\eta }^2$, the precision ofξ$\\xi$as a signal aboutω$\\omega$. Conditional on the realization of the price at date 1 and her signal,sτ$s_{\\tau }$, the expected utility of trading for an investor given her optimal trading strategy is: Proof of Proposition 2.Using Equation (22), we obtain Proof of Proposition 3.The proposition follows directly from Propositions1a