see that the direct effect of an increase inσω2$\\sigma _{\\omega }^2$andση2$\\sigma _{\\eta }^2$on price informativeness is negative. However, there is also an indirect effect: an increase inσω2$\\sigma _{\\omega }^2$andση2$\\sigma _{\\eta }^2$raises asset managers' average signals (τ¯$\\bar{\\tau }$), which positively affects price informativeness. The net effect of an increase inσω2$\\sigma _{\\omega }^2$andση2$\\sigma _{\\eta }^2$on price informativeness is therefore ambiguous. However, one can prove by contradiction that it must be positive. To see why, suppose that there is a value ofσω$\\sigma _{\\omega }$orση$\\sigma _{\\eta }$for which a marginal increase in either one of these two variables increases price informativenessI$\\cal {I}$. Then, one can see from the expression ofr(τ,τ∗)$r(\\tau,\\tau ^*)$in Equation (23) that for this value, a marginal increase in either one of these two variables reducesr(τ,τ∗)$r(\\tau,\\tau ^*)$. However, this is impossible since, using the expression ofr(τ,τ∗)$r(\\tau,\\tau ^*)$in (A23), we have shown thatr(τ,τ∗)$r(\\tau,\\tau ^*)$necessarily increases withσω$\\sigma _{\\omega }$orση$\\sigma _{\\eta }$. We conclude that for all values ofσω$\\sigma _{\\omega }$orση$\\sigma _{\\eta }$, an increase in either one of these two variables reduces price informativeness. Proof of Corollary 1.Consider the effect ofτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$on asset managers' average performance. We know from Proposition5thatτ¯(τ∗(τdmmax,c),τdmmax)$\\bar{\\tau }(\\tau ^*(\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm},c),\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm})$increases withτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$. Moreover,limτdmmax→0τ¯(τ∗(τdmmax,c),τdmmax)=τ¯0$ {\\lim _{\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}\\rightarrow 0}} \\bar{\\tau }(\\tau ^*(\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm},c),\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm})=\\bar{\\tau }_0$, becauseτ∗$\\tau ^*$goes to zero whenτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$goes to zero (sinceτ∗<τdmmax$\\tau ^* < \\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm}$), and therefore,μ∗$\\mu ^*$goes to zero whenτdmmax$\\tau ^{\\rm max}_{dm