2025-03-16 16:21:56,738 - DEBUG - Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'files': None, 'json_data': {'messages': [{'role': 'user', 'content': "你是一位总结专家。你的任务是撰写总结。\n    以下是原始文档文本：\n    \n    TITLE:Sending Out an SMS: Automatic Enrollment Experiments for Overdraft Alerts\nAbstract:At-scale field experiments at major U.K. banks show that automatic enrollment into “just-in-time” text alerts reduces unarranged overdraft and unpaid item charges 17% to 19% and arranged overdraft charges 4% to 8%, implying annual market-wide savings of £170 million to £240 million. Incremental benefits from “early-warning” alerts are statistically insignificant, although economically significant effects are not ruled out. Prior to the experiments, over half of overdrafts could have been avoided by using lower-cost liquidity available in savings and credit card accounts. Alerts help consumers achieve less than half of these potential\xa0savings.\nintroduction: Bank overdrafts are both oneof the most common forms of consumer borrowing and one of the most expensive options (Stango and Zinman (2009), Armstrong and Vickers (2012), Stango and Zinman (2014), Alan et al. (2018)). Until recently, overdrafts in the United Kingdom incurred a mix of per-transaction (£5 to £15), per-day (£0.50 to £10), per-month (£6 to £10), and interest (equivalent annual rates [EARs] of 11% to 67%) charges in addition unpaid item charges of £5 to £25 per declined transaction. Unarranged overdrafts (also referred to as unauthorized overdrafts) could be especially expensive, in excess of 10% effective interest per day, prompting a regulatory pricing intervention by the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) (FCA (2018a,2018b)). Overdraft and unpaid item charges in 2017 totaled an estimated £2.6 billion, of which 50% was paid by less than 5% of consumers (FCA (2018b)). In the United Kingdom's most economically deprived areas (as indicated by the English Index of Multiple Deprivation), the 1% heaviest users spent £380 on average in 2016 (1.9% of average household income net of housing expenses) on unarranged overdraft charges (FCA (2018a), FCA (2018b)). High effective interest rates often lead to debate about whether the rates are efficient or exploitative. (Zinman (2014) and Beshears et al. (2018) summarize evidence on both sides for payday lending.) Expensive credit can be efficient when lenders have similarly high costs due to high default rates and borrowers have a high value for additional liquidity. Neither, however, appears to be typical for overdraft borrowing. Adjusting for the risk of default, the FCA estimates that the average markups for overdrafts are three times higher than those for credit card lending or unsecured personal loans (FCA (2018b)). Moreover, previous studies show that consumers often have access to lower-cost sources of liquidity at the time of their overdraft borrowing (Stango and Zinman (2009), FCA (2018b)). A leading hypothesis for consumers' behavior is inattention to account balances (Stango and Zinman (2009), Armstrong and Vickers (2012), Stango and Zinman (2014), Grubb (2015a), Liu, Montgomery, and Srinivasan (2018)). This hypothesis is consistent with the U.K. Competition and Markets Authority's (CMA's) (2016) finding that half of U.K. overdraft users were unaware that they had recently used their overdraft facility. If inattention leads to overdrafts, then requiring banks to automatically enroll customers into overdraft text alerts should reduce overdraft charges. Such a policy was recently implemented by the CMA in 2018 and subsequently extended by the FCA in 2019 based on our study (CMA (2016), FCA (2018b)). We present two sets of at-scale field experiments that measure the effect of automatic enrollment in overdraft text alerts. The experiments were conducted in 2017 and 2018 by two large national U.K. retail banks (Banks A and B) with a combined sample of 1.1 million banking customers. The experiments automatically enrolled current (checking) account customers into a variety of “just-in-time” alerts, triggered by entry into overdraft or when a pending transaction is poised to be declined, and “early-warning” alerts, triggered by low balances before the overdraft threshold. We test both stand-alone early-warning alerts sent to consumers who do not receive a corresponding just-in-time alert and incremental early-warning alerts sent to consumers who were previously enrolled to receive a corresponding just-in-time alert. Each alert is designed to warn of either a declined transaction called an unpaid item (UI) or one of the two types of overdraft facilities offered in the United Kingdom—arranged and unarranged. Anarranged overdraft(AOD) facility is a line of credit with a borrowing limit preagreed between bank and consumer, equal to £1,000 on average at Banks A and B, which consumers automatically use when their current (checking) account balance drops below zero. Anunarranged overdraft(UOD) facility is used when a bank approves a transaction that takes the consumer past their AOD limit or, if they do not have an AOD, below zero. These experiments are complemented by descriptive evidence of consumer overdraft behavior at all six large U.K. retail banks (which served 90% of the U.K. current account market at the time) and a follow-up survey linked to the field experiments. (In SectionVof theInternet Appendix, we also analyze staggered rollouts of alerts at Banks C and D in 2015 as complementary natural experiments.1) Our primary hypothesis is that just-in-time alerts, stand-alone early-warning alerts, and incremental early-warning alerts all help consumers avoid overdraft charges. Our primary findings are twofold. First, all stand-alone alerts tested (including both just-in-time and early-warning alerts) significantly reduced the overdraft charges that they were designed to warn of, and the effects are large. Automatic enrollment into stand-alone alerts reduced the sum of UOD charges and UI charges by 5% to 19% (17% to 19% for just-in-time alerts), and reduced AOD charges by 2% to 8% (4% to 8% for just-in-time alerts).2(Unless otherwise noted, stated ranges reflect variation in point estimates across treatments rather than confidence intervals.) Second, evidence for incremental benefits of adding an early-warning alert when a corresponding just-in-time alert is already in place is weaker—incremental early-warning alerts have no statistically significant effects. Importantly, this result may reflect a lack of statistical power rather than a lack of effectiveness, and thus economically significant effects cannot be ruled out. In additional analysis, we investigate three secondary questions. First, which customers benefit from alerts? Policymakers are most concerned about low-income customers and heavy overdrafters. It is possible that alerts benefit these groups little despite delivering substantial benefits on average. For instance, low-income consumers may have limited available cash to transfer into an overdrawn account upon receiving an alert. Alerts may also be uninformative for many heavy overdrafters if they primarily overdraft intentionally rather than due to inattention, as suggested by the finding in Liu, Montgomery, and Srinivasan (2018) that overdrafting at a U.S. bank is negatively correlated with balance checks for light overdrafters but not for heavy overdrafters. Nevertheless, we find that alerts do benefit both customers with low account inflows (our proxy for income, the monthly sum of funds deposited into a customer's observed accounts) and heavy overdrafters. In fact, absolute fee reductions increase with pretreatment overdraft usage, although less than proportionally, so that percentage fee reductions are the smallest for the heaviest overdraft users. Consistent with this result, we find that alerts reduce days per month in overdraft across a wide range of the distribution, reducing the likelihood of exceeding zero overdraft days in a month as well as the likelihood of exceeding 15 overdraft days in a month. We also find that customers with high pretreatment measures of “close calls,” whereby account balances approach or cross overdraft thresholds without accruing charges, experience larger benefits from alerts. Relatedly, low average balances and, for those with positive average balances, high variability in account balances in the pretreatment period are associated with a larger absolute benefit from alerts. Finally, for many (though not all) treatments, lower account engagement as measured by account logins is associated with larger benefits from alerts. Second, how do customers react to alerts to achieve the measured savings? Bank A login data show that alerts draw customers' attention to their accounts, increasing same-day account logins by 10% to 53% (0.13 to 0.49 logins). Bank A transaction data show that spending reductions are economically small but that each alert triggers up to an additional 0.27 transfers (each averaging £465) into the account on the same day.3Although we cannot rule out economically significant effects from early-warning alerts, this result helps explain why their effects might be small: the theoretical benefit of incremental early-warning alerts is that they allow customers to avoid overdraft by cutting spending in advance, but in practice consumers' spending is relatively inelastic to these alerts. One reason spending may be relatively inelastic to these alerts is that the amount of early warning that they provide is often too short—up to one-third of early-warning alerts arrive the same day as the corresponding just-in-time alert. Third, do alerts eliminate overdrafting mistakes? In other words, when alerts are active, is all remaining overdraft borrowing optimal conditional on available liquidity?4We find that just-in-time alerts reduce days in overdraft by 4% to 21%, while the FCA (2018b) finds that 50% to 60% of days in overdraft could be avoided by using savings or less costly credit card borrowing. This suggests that alerts eliminate less than half of overdraft charges arising from frictions such as inattention rather than from optimal borrowing. Moreover, while we do not observe savings or credit card balances in our data, the 5% of customers with an overdraft facility for whom we observe a second current account provide additional supporting evidence that overdraft mistakes are prevalent even when alerts are active. Extrapolating our primary findings to all consumers in the market using 2017 charges as a baseline suggests that just-in-time alerts could reduce annual overdraft and UI charges by £170 million to £240 million, of which £48 million to £110 million is due to the just-in-time AOD alerts.5Based on these findings, in 2019 the FCA expanded the CMA's mandate for just-in-time UOD and UI alerts to cover more banks (by reducing the\nI. Related Literature: The only overdraft alert experiment that we are aware of is a contemporaneous study by Ben-David, Mintz, and Sade (2021) of e-mail alerts sent by the personal finance application Mint to a sample of its users. In contrast to their study, ours is “at scale” in terms of sample representativeness and implementation (Muralidharan and Niehaus (2017)): our sample population is representative of the U.K. banking customers affected by an opt-out policy for overdraft text alerts. Our tested text alerts are the same alerts that would be implemented by the same bank IT departments in response to regulation. We estimate larger effect sizes than Ben-David, Mintz, and Sade (2021), consistent with the fact that text messages are opened by 99% of recipients8while Mint's e-mails were opened by only 28% to 31% of users. Our study therefore provides a tighter lower bound on the fraction of overdrafting due to inattention. (Even with 99% reach, this is only a lower bound because a recipient can open a text message without redirecting their full attention to their current account balance.) Like alerts, reminders can draw their recipient's attention and induce them to take action. Reminders have been found to be effective in a wide range of settings. Reminders can improve medical appointment attendance (Reekie and Devlin (1998), Bourne et al. (2011)), loan repayment (Cadena and Schoar (2011), Karlan, Morten, and Zinman (2015), Medina (2021)), influenza vaccination rates (Szilagyi and Adams (2012)), library returns (Apesteguia, Funk, and Iriberri (2013)), dental appointment creation (Altmann and Traxler (2014)), medication adherence (Pop-Eleches et al. (2011), Bobrow et al. (2016)), savings (Karlan et al. (2016), Kast, Meier, and Pomeranz (2018)), and gym attendance (Calzolari and Nardotto (2017)). However, reminders are sometimes ineffective in some of the same settings (Karlan, Morten, and Zinman (2015), Bursztyn et al. (2019)) or have unintended consequences (Damgaard and Gravert (2018), Medina (2021)). See Hummel and Maedche (2019) and DellaVigna and Linos (2022) for meta-analyses of additional reminder studies. Unlike reminders, alerts contain real-time information that is not already known, and thus individuals cannot replicate them using calendar software if they are not provided by banks. A variety of studies inform optimal alert or reminder design by testing variations in message content. For instance, message effectiveness can increase with simplification (Ben-David, Mintz, and Sade (2021)) and personalization (Karlan, Morten, and Zinman (2015)). In our setting, policymakers had no intention to specify exact message text, so we tested the language chosen by banks would likely be implemented for mandated alerts. Our study is one of only a few to our knowledge that investigate alert or reminder design with respect to timing (Karlan, Morten, and Zinman (2015), Karlan et al. (2016), Guyton et al. (2017), Medina (2021)). Most relevant is Medina's (2021) finding in support of early reminders— sending five credit card bill reminders spread over the month preceding the due date is more effective at inducing on-time payment than sending only the last two reminders.\nII. Data, Background, and Methods: Overdraft facilities are borrowing facilities tied to consumers' current (checking) accounts. In the United Kingdom, 97% of adults have a current account and the product is universally used for receiving income, holding funds, and making payments (CMA (2016)). Over two-thirds of accounts have an overdraft facility, which can be either arranged or unarranged. Transactions that take a consumer past their AOD limit or, if they do not have an AOD, below zero, are automatically rejected for a customer without a UOD facility. For those with a UOD facility, such transactions are processed at the bank's discretion based on how much credit would need to be extended. Either the bank extends credit to process the transaction as a UOD, or the bank rejects the transaction and the customer typically incurs a UI fee.9 TableIshows how AOD and UOD fees were structured at each of the six major U.K. banks in May 2018, just after our field experiments concluded and prior to recent regulation (effective April 2020) restricting overdraft pricing to a simple interest rate. (See TableAIIIfor 2023 prices.) In 2018, AOD fees could include daily charges of £0.50 to £3.00 per day in overdraft, monthly charges of £6 to £10 per billing cycle in overdraft, and interest charges on overdraft balances with EARs of 11% to 67%. UOD fees could include daily charges of £5 to £10 per day in overdraft, interest charges on overdraft balances with EARs of 16% to 19%, and paid item charges of £5 to £15 per cleared transaction that results in a UOD balance. UI charges could be £5 to £25 per declined transaction. Checkmarks in TableIindicate which of these fees each of the six major U.K. banks utilized in their overdraft fee structure. Several other features affect total monthly charges. No overdraft charges are incurred unless an account is in overdraft after an end-of-day grace period and the balance falls below a “buffer zone.” Buffer zones were typically £10 to £15. Moreover, beginning in September 2017, banks were required to set their own monthly caps for the sum of UOD and UI fees called maximum monthly charges (MMC). MMC ranged from £50 to £95. Some banks also voluntarily capped monthly AOD charges. No MMC is listed for Llyods Banking Group (LBG) because it ended UOD in November 2017.10 In collaboration with the FCA, we obtained a one-year representative panel of 1.5 million adult account holders in 2015 from the six largest retail banks. For each individual sampled from a bank, the data include all current accounts held at the bank and all of their transactions in 2015. Descriptive statistics for this observational data set are shown in TableII. These six banks served a combined 90% of account holders in the United Kingdom, providing us extensive coverage of the U.K. consumer population (CMA (2016)). All six banks have a national branch network and retail presence, and offer all mainstream retail financial products alongside current accounts. Consumer surveys indicate that there is little to differentiate their current account offerings in terms of quality (CMA (2016)). Customer characteristics and overdraft usage are relatively similar across the six banks. Mean age and gender proportions are similar to those for all banks (across banks, mean age is 45 to 50 years, the proportion female is 0.48 to 0.52). Banks' policies on overdraft facilities differ slightly, but the proportion of customers with an AOD facility is similar across banks (0.47 to 0.63). The (highly skewed) distribution of total annual overdraft charges is also remarkably similar across banks, with customers up to the 75thpercentile paying relatively little (£8 to £36 per year), rising steeply for those at higher percentiles (£223 to £363 per year at the 95thpercentile). FigureA1shows the 2015 distribution of AOD and UOD charges for all six banks. Note that the six-bank panel data set we use is a subset of that used by the FCA to complete its High-Cost Credit Review, as their panel extended a second year to the end of 2016 and was linked to information about customers' other financial accounts via credit reporting agencies. Hence, for more extensive descriptive statistics (including many we cite in this paper), see FCA (2018b).11 Figure1shows the timing of policy changes that affected the availability of overdraft alerts relative to our observational data, field experiments, and survey. U.K. government policy mandated that, by March 2012, all large U.K. banks provide their customers opt-in access to three types of text message alerts.12The first two are just-in-time alerts, which are sent (i) when customers enter UOD and (ii) when transactions are scheduled to be rejected and UI charges are pending. The third is an early-warning or low-balance alert, sent when a customer's balance falls below a threshold (Department for Business, Investment & Skills (BIS) and HM Treasury (2011)). Although causal impact estimates for the opt-in policy are not available, they are likely to be modest as voluntary sign-up rates for these alerts two years after their introduction range from 1% to 8% (Caflisch et al. (2018)).13 In 2016, the CMA mandated that all large U.K. banks automatically enroll their customers in the just-in-time UOD and UI alerts by February 2018, thereby changing the policy for these alerts from opt-in to opt-out (CMA (2016)). Effective December 2019, following the release of our findings in a policy paper (Adams et al. (2018)), AOD just-in-time alerts were also mandated on an opt-out basis by the FCA (FCA (2018b)). The effect size estimates in earlier versions of this paper directly informed the design of this policy. Early-warning alerts remain available on an opt-in basis. The arrival of just-in-time alerts coincides with an intraday grace period. The CMA requires that the timing of alerts with respect to UOD grace-period deadlines must “allow customers a reasonable opportunity to take action to avoid or reduce charges” (CMA (2016, paragraph 15.38)).14If sufficient funds are deposited sufficiently early on the day an alert is received, overdraft charges are avoided as they are assessed only when the end-of-day balance is in overdraft. Similarly, rejected transactions will clear without incurring UI charges when banks make second attempts to process the transactions later in the day. For a hypothetical consumer who has both AOD and UOD facilities and is enrolled in all alerts, Figure2illustrates when just-in-time and early-warning alerts are sent as the consumer's account balance decreases. We say that the alert labeled “UOD/UI early warning” provides early warning for UI in addition to UOD because extension of credit through a UOD facility is at the bank's discretion and is typically limited—meaning that any account on the verge of incurring UOD charges is also on the verge of incurring UI charges. Under FCA auspices, we conducted two sets of field experiments over the period 2017 to 2018 in collaboration with two of the six top U.K. national retail banks (Banks A and B). The FCA's objective was to test whether automatic enrollment into alerts in addition to those already mandated by the CMA (just-in-time UOD and UI alerts) would be beneficial to consumers. The treatments, trial dates, and sample sizes were agreed with each bank in a “Terms of Reference” document signed by the bank and the FCA, which serves as our preregistration of key study details (see SectionIXof theInternet Appendix). An ethics review was conducted in accordance with established FCA procedure.15 After sampling was complete, both banks automatically enrolled treatment group customers into treatment alerts at the beginning of November 2017 (we provide details on the structure of treatments in the following section). For shared bank accounts, all account holders with a registered mobile number receive alerts. Upon enrollment, both banks sent an e-mail notifying automatically enrolled customers that they would now be receiving alerts. Bank A also allowed its customers to opt-out by responding to a text message within a two-day window at the start of the experiment. Both banks shared a preagreed data set on all individuals in control and treatment groups with the FCA. This data set includes six months of pretreatment data and five months of posttreatment data. The data include all transactions during the sample period and contain the same variables as the 2015 observational data set with some small differences between banks. Bank A was able to share with us the date that a particular alert was sent; Bank B was able to share with us any changes that customers made to the threshold level of their early-warning alerts.Internet AppendixTableIA.XXIreports sample descriptive statistics for each bank. The experiments let us measure the incremental benefit of a treatment alert relative to the overdraft alerts already in use in both treatment and control groups. We refer to the latter type of alerts as “baseline” alerts. Figure3shows the experimental timing of automatic enrollment into both treatment alerts and baseline alerts. Months 1 to 6 (May to October 2017) are the pretreatment period; months 7 to 11 (November 2017 to March 2018) are the treatment period. The alerts in use at baseline varied over the 11-month sample period as both banks had\nIII. Results: Prior to automatic enrollment, cumulative opt-in rates for any alert across the six major banks were at most 8% (Caflisch et al. (2018)).21During our treatment period, cumulative opt-out rates were all below 10%. As a result, automatic enrollment dramatically raised enrollment in all treatments. Opt-in and opt-out rates reported in TableAIIimply that automatic enrollment raised enrollment by 95 to 99 percentage points across Bank B treatments and by at least 91 to 93 percentage points across Bank A treatments.22In contrast, Bank A's prompted enrollment treatment was less successful by an order of magnitude, leading only 8.7% of treated customers to enroll. (For survey results about consumers' reasons for opting-out, see SectionIof theInternet Appendix. For a comparison of customers who opt-in, opt-out, or follow the default, seeInternet AppendixTableIA.XXIV.) Although cumulative opt-out rates are all below 10%, opt-out rates are much larger at Bank A (6.9% to 9.2%) than at Bank B (0.1% to 1.6%). The higher opt-out rates for Bank A are not surprising, as Bank A customers could easily opt-out by replying to a text message at the start of the enrollment period, whereas Bank B customers had to log in to their accounts to change settings. The comparison between bank opt-out rates shows that the ease with which consumers can opt-out strongly affects opt-out rates but that the vast majority of consumers remain opted-in to the alerts, even when opting-out is made as easy as possible. TableVreports our main results: the ITT effect in pounds sterling per month on observed AOD charges, UOD/UI charges, and total charges in the months after automatic enrollment in alerts. Two patterns are clear. First, all tested stand-alone alerts (both just-in-time alerts and early-warning alerts) reduce total monthly charges by a statistically and economically significant amount: 27 to 56 pence per month or 3% to 19% percent. (Effects are statistically significant at the 1% level.23) In contrast, all tested incremental early-warning alerts have statistically insignificant effects, although imprecision means we cannot rule out economically significant effects of similar magnitude. Second, alerts primarily affect the charges they target (highlighted in gray): although there may be some spillover effects to other charges, they have small point estimates and are statistically insignificant. Thus, estimated absolute effects for targeted charges are similar to those for total charges. We therefore focus, hereafter, on targeted charges, for which relative effect sizes are more comparable across treatments. Moving beyond these two clear patterns, we find no statistical difference between alerts that differ only in timing. Treatments 2 and 3 both test a stand-alone AOD alert at Bank B with similar wording, but vary whether the alert is a just-in-time alert (treatment 2) or an early-warning alert with a £100 threshold (treatment 3). Point estimates suggest that the just-in-time alert is 1.6 times as effective as the early-warning alert in reducing AOD charges, and 1.2 times as effective in reducing total charges, but neither difference is statistically significant. Based on these findings, in 2019 the FCA expanded the CMA's mandate for just-in-time UOD and UI alerts to cover more banks (by reducing the size threshold for which the regulation applies) and added a mandate for just-in-time AOD alerts, but chose not to mandate any early-warning alerts (FCA (2018b)). Our point estimates predict that these mandated alerts reduce AOD charges by 4% to 8% and reduce UOD and UI charges by 17% to 19%. Using 2017 market-wide charges as a baseline, this implies consumer savings of £170 million to £240 million (see footnote for details). In this section, we use secondary outcomes to conduct a robustness check on our main results, and to examine substitutability between early-warning and just-in-time alerts. TableVIreports the effect of automatic enrollment for a stand-alone alert on secondary outcomes: inferred (rather than observed) targeted charges, number of UIs, days spent in overdraft, and number of overdraft episodes of different lengths, all measured on a per-month basis. For treatment 9, which tests an early-warning UOD alert using design A, columns (6) and (7) report separate treatment effects when the alert was stand-alone during months 7 to 9 (premandate) and when the alert was incremental during months 10 and 11 (postmandate, after Bank A automatically enrolled all customers in just-in-time UOD alerts). Results for inferred charges are similar to our main results using observed charges. Stand-alone alerts cause significant reductions in charges that are matched by significant reductions in days spent in overdraft, as well as in significant reductions in UIs for those alerts targeting UOD and UI charges. For inferred charges, treatment 9 shows a sharp difference pre- versus postmandate:24Postmandate, the estimated treatment effect is statistically insignificant, and the 95% confidence interval rules out a treatment effect larger than 14 pence per month. Premandate, however, the 95% confidence interval implies that automatic enrollment reduces UOD and UI charges by 22 to 38 pence per month. While a 14 pence per month effect would be economically significant, this shows that when we vary whether an alert is stand-alone or incremental, while holding the customer sample and other dimensions of alert design fixed, the stand-alone version provides a significantly larger effect.25This finding is reasonable because it means that just-in-time and early-warning alerts are partial substitutes—consistent with the fact that if a customer responds effectively to an early-warning alert, they may stop a just-in-time alert from being sent. Turning to overdraft episodes, the length of an episode is the number of consecutive closing daily balances that are in overdraft. One-or-more-day overdraft episodes incur charges, but zero-day episodes, in which overdraft is entered and then exited again within the same day, are merely “close calls” that do not incur charges due to the grace period. TableVIshows that all stand-alone alerts significantly reduce the number of one-or-more-day episodes. In contrast, treatment effects on zero-day episodes vary in a way that shows early-warning alerts cause customers to resolve overdraft episodes earlier than just-in-time alerts do. First, compare treatments 2 and 3. These test Bank B's AOD alerts, which are similar apart from their timing. The just-in-time alert (treatment 2) causes a nearly identical increase in zero-day episodes as its reduction in one-or-more-day episodes, while the early-warning alert (treatment 3) has no effect on zero-day episodes. The increase in zero-day episodes in treatment 2 is mechanical: just-in-time alerts are sent too late to avoid overdrafting altogether, so avoided one-or-more-day episodes must be resolved as zero-day episodes. The fact that treatment 3 does not affect zero-day alerts implies that early-warning alert recipients do respond earlier—in time to avoid overdraft episodes before they begin. Second, compare Bank A's early-warning UOD/UI alert in the premandate period (column (6)) to the postmandate period (column (7)). The estimates show that early-warning alerts lead customers to act early and resolve overdraft episodes before they occur, whether a just-in-time alert is already in place or not. However, when the just-in-time alert is already in place (postmandate), this early action has a smaller financial benefit because it primarily avoids costless zero-day episodes. These zero-day episodes would otherwise have been resolved following just-in-time alerts that now are no longer sent. Note that, counter to expectation, Bank B's just-in-time UOD/UI alerts (columns (4) and (5)) do not increase zero-day episodes as much as they decrease one-or-more-day episodes. This likely results from Bank B's implementation of the UOD grace period.26 Above, we show that alerts help consumers on average, addressing the primary research question of our paper. Our first secondary question, presented in the introduction, asks which consumers benefit and if automatic enrollment helps those consumers who policymakers care most about—those with low income or high overdraft charges. In this section, we show how the impact of automatic enrollment varies with pretreatment measures of account usage and customer-specific characteristics, which lets us answer this question and shed light on who alerts help most. Due to the lack of statistical significance of incremental alerts, hereafter we focus primarily on the six treatments that test stand-alone alerts and, unless otherwise noted, for treatment 9 we include only the first three treatment months when the tested alert was stand-alone. First, we divide the sample into three groups based on our proxy for income, namely, account inflows (TableVII). Account inflows is the monthly sum of funds deposited into a customer's account, which we average over the pretreatment period. This proxy is imperfect because it omits income deposited to unobserved accounts such as savings accounts and it includes transfers between accounts that are not income. While there is no clear correlation between effect size and account inflows that is consistent across treatments, effects are economically and statistically significant in the lowest account-inflows group for five of six stand-alone alert treatments, including all just-in-time alerts. Thus, consumers with low account inflows do benefit from alerts. Second, we consider pretreatment charge levels. For this analysis, we split the population into three groups: rare, occasional, and frequent overdrafters. Rare overdrafters are individuals who have no charges in the pretreatment period. Occasional overdrafters have charges below the pretreatment median (conditional on charges being positive), while heavy overdrafters\nIV. Conclusion: Automatically enrolling U.K. banking customers into just-in-time AOD alerts reduces AOD charges 4% to 8%, and enrolling customers into just-in-time UOD and UI alerts reduces UOD and UI charges 17% to 19%. Extrapolated to the entire U.K. market in 2017, this represents potential annual consumer savings of £170 million to £240 million. Savings from alerts increase with customers' pretreatment overdraft propensity and decrease with customers' pretreatment average balances, but less than proportionally, so that frequent overdrafters and customers with low average balances benefit most from alerts but end up responsible for an even larger share of total overdraft charges after alerts are in place. Among those with positive average balances, savings from alerts are also larger for customers with high pretreatment variability in balances. While it is not clear whether low-income consumers benefit more or less than high-income consumers, it is clear that customers with low account inflows do benefit. Together, these results suggest that low-income consumers, heavy overdrafters, and financially vulnerable consumers who policymakers may most want to help do share in the benefits of alerts. Why did so few customers (less than 8% (Caflisch et al. (2018))) take advantage of these benefits by actively opting-in to alerts prior to automatic enrollment? The low active opt-in rates could be due to a combination of three possible factors: (i) high nuisance costs of receiving alerts, (ii) high hassle costs of enrolling in alerts (consistent with one coauthor's personal experience that opting-in was not easy), and (iii) informational or behavioral frictions (such as unawareness of the option to enroll, underestimation of the benefits of enrolling, or procrastination), consistent with Bronchetti et al.'s (2023) finding that individuals underinvest in attention aids. Of the three possible factors, only high nuisance costs could cause automatic enrollment to reduce consumer surplus—due to consumers who are irritated by alerts but fail to opt-out. This seems unlikely, however, because the nuisance cost would have to be substantial (e.g., exceeding 77 pence per alert for Bank A's just-in-time AOD alert). Moreover, survey respondents (a group admittedly selected based on willingness to participate) who do not opt-out of alerts show broad agreement that alerts are helpful. The large impact of alerts shows that, in their absence, a substantial portion of the high effective interest rates paid for overdraft borrowing do not reflect a high value for credit but rather inattention to account balances. Moreover, evidence suggests that alerts eliminate less than half of overdraft charges arising from frictions such as inattention rather than optimal borrowing. As a result, there remains scope for alternative interventions to further reduce borrowing mistakes, such as sweep accounts that automatically transfer funds across accounts when needed. In principle, customers could respond to alerts by depositing funds into their accounts or by reducing spending. There is greater scope for avoiding borrowing charges via reduced spending if one starts cutting spending before account balances are depleted. We therefore expected substantial incremental benefits for early-warning alerts triggered when balances fall within £50 or £100 of an overdraft threshold. However, while we cannot rule out economically significant benefits of incremental early-warning alerts, such effects are not statistically detectable in our study. A potential explanation is that spending is not an important margin of response to alerts. Instead, transfers of funds (which are instantaneous in the United Kingdom) account for most of the savings in overdraft charges. It is an open question as to why consumers' current account spending is not more elastic, as the FCA has shown that consumers could avoid about half of their overdrafts by shifting some of their current account spending onto their lower-cost credit cards without cutting consumption (FCA (2018b)). One possibility is that customers do not realize that their effective overdraft interest rates are higher than their credit card borrowing rates because overdraft charges were quoted in pounds per chargeable event (per day or per transaction, etc.), which are not easily comparable to credit card interest rates. This is one motivation for the recent FCA policy (effective April 2020) requiring banks to price overdraft borrowing using interest rates rather than daily charges and encouraging them to disclose overdraft interest rates to consumers as an EAR (FCA (2019)). (TablesIandAIIIdescribe overdraft pricing before and after the regulatory change.) The hope is that by making overdraft rates easily comparable to credit card borrowing rates, banks will be forced to offer overdraft rates that are competitive with credit card rates. Our headline findings for policymakers are twofold. First, given intraday grace periods, automatic enrollment in just-in-time alerts provides a large consumer benefit without offsetting consumer harm. Second, any incremental benefit from additional early-warning alerts is not statistically detectable in our study. Based on these findings, in 2019 the FCA expanded the CMA's mandate for just-in-time UOD and UI alerts to cover more banks (by reducing the size threshold for which the regulation applies) and added a mandate for just-in-time AOD alerts, but chose not to mandate any early-warning alerts (FCA (2018b)). Our experimental tests of alerts do not reveal what banks' equilibrium pricing responses will be once alerts are in place across the market. Since alert mandates represent a regulated cut in hidden charge revenue, a natural concern is that banks will raise overdraft fees or other charges to offset the lost revenue. Nevertheless, we are optimistic that U.K. retail banks will respond to the regulated cut in hidden charges similarly to U.S. retail banks, which did not adjust prices to offset 2009 CARD Act reductions in hidden credit card charges (Agarwal et al. (2015)). Investigating whether our optimism is borne out in practice is left for future work. Editors: Stefan Nagel, Philip Bond, Amit Seru, and Wei Xiong\nAppendix: \nSample Statistics and Overdraft Pricing: Sample deletions: TableAIshows how we construct our estimation sample by dropping observations with inconsistent or missing data and dropping customers who lack an active primary account, have defaulted, or are using their account for business purposes. Treatment and control means: TableAIIreports average monthly total observed overdraft charges for each treatment and control group, opt-in rates for control groups and the treatment group in prompted enrollment treatment 11, as well as opt-out rates for treated groups in automatic enrollment treatments 1 to 10. Overdraft fee distribution: FigureA1shows the distribution of customers' monthly AOD and UOD charges at each of the six major U.K. banks in 2015. 2023 overdraft pricing: TableAIIIshows how AOD and UOD fees are structured for basic account types at each of the six major U.K. banks in July 2023, when overdraft pricing is restricted to a simple interest rate. EARs for basic accounts are 35% to 39.94%. Premium accounts, student accounts, and recent graduate accounts sometimes offer EAR discounts of 10 to 20 percentage points or, alternatively, buffers of up to £3,000 for which interest charges do not accrue. Most banks do not offer UOD borrowing (apart from a small buffer) or charge the same EAR as for AOD. UI fees are either zero or a maximum of £2.15 per month at Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS).\nSupporting Information: Appendix S1: Internet Appendix. Replication Code. Please note: The publisher is not responsible for the content or functionality of any supporting information supplied by the authors. Any queries (other than missing content) should be directed to the corresponding author for the article.\nREFERENCES: \n\n\n你需要做出全面、简单、直接的总结。总结字数不超过250字。分析给你的学术论文，用一句话进行总结，回答以下问题：该论文研究的是什么领域，它想要解决什么问题，之前是如何解决的，作者是如何解决的，并重点关注作者提出的方法。 \n\n[Warning] 最后，我想给你一些撰写学术博客的提示作为参考：  \n1. 使用第三人称和对话语气，要有趣并吸引读者的兴趣。\n2. 简化复杂概念：保持简单明了。 字数限制为250字。\n3. 请注意，这篇文章不是你写的。\n"}, {'role': 'assistant', 'content': '这篇论文研究消费者金融行为领域，探讨如何通过短信提醒减少银行用户因疏忽导致的透支费用。传统解决方案依赖用户主动订阅提醒（自愿加入），但注册率不足8%。作者与英国两大银行合作开展百万人规模实验，采用"自动加入+允许退出"机制测试两类短信：实时透支警报（触发时发送）和余额预警（透支前发送）。结果显示，自动推送实时警报使非计划透支费用下降17-19%（年节省1.7-2.4亿英镑），而提前预警的额外效果不显著。研究创新点在于通过自然实验验证"默认选择"在金融产品中的应用效能，发现实时警报通过促进即时转账而非减少消费来实现费用节省，为监管部门推行强制警报政策提供了关键证据。'}, {'role': 'user', 'content': '\n根据你提供的总结，为这篇论文的分析想出一个通用的标题。这个标题需要涵盖文章中最具创新性的元素，并吸引读者的注意力。创建一个引人注目的标题，这个标题需要像新闻标题一样引人注目，而不是文章标题的重述。限制在25个字以内。\n格式限制：\n1. 只需给出你写的标题，不需要其他废话\n2. **{你的给定标题}**\n'}], 'model': 'deepseek-reasoner', 'stream': False}}
